The Institute of Internal Auditors (IIA) has commended the government for the planned huge transformation aimed to enhance capacity and efficiency in various internal audit departments. The IIA President, Ms Zelia Njeza said on Thursday the budget proposal tabled by the Finance and Planning Minister Dr Mwigulu Nchemba in the National Assembly on Tuesday worth to be hailed. "We commend the government for sending the proposals to the House to transform internal auditing, starting with the office of the Internal Auditor General (IAG), that would ultimately yield appropriate and expected results in expenditure management," Ms Zelia said. Ms Zelia, also the IIA Chairperson, said the public should expect huge changes in internal auditing department and the way auditors work once the proposed transformations are approved. She appealed to all auditors to prepare themselves in their day to day obligations to support the government aimed to increase efficiency of the auditing sector. Dr Nchemba said when tabling 2022/23 budget that the Controller and Auditor General’s (CAG) report revealed some shortfalls in government spending particularly on bulky procurement and development projects. “The government…realized some shortcomings in compliance and financial audits. Whereas in some circumstances all procedures, rules as well as audit requirements are adhered to, yet there are incidents of misuse of public funds,” Dr Nchemba said. To address the problem, the government said will review procurement procedures and ensure value for money is observed across the board. The Minister also said they’ll review the scheme of service of Internal Auditors. In the same way, facilitate its participation in bench marking programs from peer countries. “These interventions will ensure the department executes its mandates efficiently and independently. (And also IAG) to be assigned an independent vote in order to strengthen and improve operational performance,” he said.